@Barry Ancona 
Well, you bring up an interesting point here about the usual orientation of Major League Baseball stadiums and the possible relation to the term “southpaw”. I first became aware of this concept after attending a game at Wahconah Park in Pittsfield, MA. That stadium has hosted a variety of lower-level minor league baseball teams (e.g. Pittsfield Mets 1989-2001) but is better known as the site of the first intercollegiate baseball game between Amherst-Williams in 1859. The place was constructed before the advent of field lighting so no harm was seen in orienting the diamond (hence the batter) due west, toward the setting sun. (It is one of only two professional parks facing west, the other being Sam Lynn Ballpark in Bakersfield, CA.) . Your M-W and other dictionaries mention the common perception a relation of field orientation this to this term, but point out it is predated by its use in boxing. For a nice discussion of the origin of the term “southpaw” , see:

